			       ------------------
			      OfficeFloor Tutorials
			       ------------------
			      Daniel Sagenschneider
			       ------------------

OfficeFloor Tutorials

  The tutorials show how to progressively add OfficeFloor capabilities to an existing
  {{{https://spring.io/projects/spring-boot}Spring Boot}} application.  Spring's dependency
  injection, security, persistence, and all other Spring configuration remain intact at every
  stage — OfficeFloor enriches, not replaces.

  OfficeFloor extends dependency injection with two further kinds of injection:

   * <<Function injection>> — compose plain Java methods into a request-handling pipeline declared
     entirely in a YAML file.  The YAML is the specification: readable without opening any Java file,
     which is especially valuable when working with AI coding tools.

   * <<Thread injection>> — assign dedicated thread pools to steps based solely on their
     dependencies.  Socket threads never block on database calls.

  The journey is structured as follows:

  [[1]] <<Spring Boot>> — Add OfficeFloor REST YAML composition to your existing Spring Boot
        application.  No migration required.

  [[2]] <<Spring in OfficeFloor>> — Host your Spring beans inside the OfficeFloor runtime.  All
        existing Spring configuration continues to work; further OfficeFloor capabilities become
        available.

  [[3]] <<Native OfficeFloor>> — Optional.  If there is interest in removing the Spring dependency
        entirely, explore the full breadth of native OfficeFloor functionality.

  [[4]] <<OfficeFloor Features>> — Advanced capabilities available in the OfficeFloor runtime:
        reactive streams and polyglot procedure logic.

  [[5]] <<Cloud and Deployment>> — Deploy OfficeFloor applications to cloud platforms and
        cloud-native datastores.

  []

  REST endpoints are declared as YAML configuration files throughout this journey.  This allows
  teams to work concurrently on separate endpoint files and gives AI tooling the context it needs to
  generate and modify endpoint code accurately.

  All tutorials are part of the OfficeFloor continuous builds and their source can be found
  {{{http://github.com/officefloor/OfficeFloor/tree/master/officefloor/tutorials}here}}.


* Phase 1: Spring Boot

  For developers already using Spring Boot, this is the starting point.  The
  {{{../officefloor-spring-boot-starter/index.html}OfficeFloor REST Spring Boot Starter}} adds REST
  YAML composition to your existing Spring Boot application without requiring any code migration.
  Your Spring beans, security, persistence, and all other Spring configuration remain unchanged;
  OfficeFloor simply takes over the declaration of REST endpoints via YAML files.

*--------------------------------------------------------------+------------------------------------------------------------+------------------------------+
|| Tutorial                                                    || Description                                               || Covered
*--------------------------------------------------------------+------------------------------------------------------------+------------------------------+
